\chapter{SYSTEM ANALYSIS}

\section{EXISTING SYSTEM}
The existing postal sorting system predominantly relies on manual operations involving human personnel who inspect, interpret, and sort physical mail based on the destination address or pin code written on parcels and envelopes. This method, although functional, is significantly time-consuming, labor-intensive, and error-prone, particularly in high-volume postal centers or logistics hubs handling thousands of items daily.
In the conventional setup, staff members visually examine each parcel to read the recipient’s address and manually determine the appropriate bin or route for sorting. This process demands constant concentration and accuracy and becomes increasingly inefficient when dealing with poor handwriting, worn-out labels, or damaged packages. Any delay or mistake in reading and interpreting the pin code can result in misrouting, delivery delays, or even lost parcels, affecting customer satisfaction and operational trust.
Furthermore, this traditional system lacks any form of automation, centralized data storage, or tracking logs, making it difficult to monitor performance metrics, trace past sorting actions, or analyze error patterns. Supervisors are unable to audit the sorting process effectively, as there is no digital record of who handled a parcel, when it was sorted, or where it was directed. This lack of transparency and accountability can lead to inefficiencies, especially in larger networks.
Another significant limitation is the absence of real-time feedback or error detection mechanisms. If a mistake occurs—such as assigning a parcel to the wrong bin—there is no system to catch or rectify the error immediately. Additionally, staff training in such systems is largely informal and does not leverage digital simulation or visualization, making it harder for new employees to learn or understand operational flow efficiently.
In terms of reporting, the current system generally depends on manual documentation, paper-based records, or isolated spreadsheets maintained by individual operators. This approach makes it difficult to consolidate data, identify trends, or generate reliable performance summaries for management review.
Despite some organizations attempting minor digital enhancements—like barcode-based sorting or camera-assisted tracking—many postal offices and small courier services still use this outdated manual model due to budget constraints, lack of infrastructure, or technical know-how. Consequently, these systems struggle to meet modern demands for speed, traceability, and accuracy in mail processing.

\section{PROPOSED SYSTEM}
The proposed system aims to modernize and automate the process of postal sorting by leveraging advanced technologies such as Optical Character Recognition (OCR), machine learning logic, and real-time data visualization. Traditional postal sorting methods rely heavily on manual labor, making the process time-consuming, error-prone, and inefficient. The developed solution introduces a fully automated pipeline that captures parcel images, extracts address and pin code information using OCR, and sorts items into their respective destination bins based on pin code mappings. This automation significantly enhances sorting accuracy, saves time, and reduces human errors. The system is particularly beneficial for logistics centers and postal departments seeking to improve operational efficiency. By integrating image acquisition, preprocessing, and pin code extraction, the solution ensures faster processing, improved reliability, and greater operational performance.

The AI-based postal sorting system is designed with a role-based access control mechanism that distinguishes between two types of users: Admin and Postal Staff, each with clearly defined responsibilities and interfaces. The Admin plays a supervisory role and is primarily responsible for managing user accounts. This includes adding new staff members, editing existing user details, and deleting staff accounts when necessary. Admins can also view the complete sorting history generated by the postal staff and monitor login activities for administrative oversight. This role ensures controlled access and accountability within the system, maintaining operational security and structured user management.

On the other hand, the Postal Staff interact with the system to carry out the actual sorting process. They can either capture images of letters and parcels in real-time using a webcam or upload existing images from the local system. Once uploaded, the system automatically processes the image and displays the extracted address and pin code using OCR. The staff can then view the extracted details, which are presented in a clean and readable format for verification. A key highlight of the project is the animated visualization that shows the parcel moving towards its designated bin on the screen based on the pin code logic. This real-time feedback not only confirms successful sorting but also enhances user interactivity and system engagement. In addition, Postal Staff can view the contents of each bin, export sorting reports in PDF format, and review previously sorted items through the sorted history section. This structured workflow empowers staff to manage parcel sorting efficiently while ensuring transparency and traceability across all stages of the process.

The core functionality of the system is driven by the integration of Optical Character Recognition (OCR), specifically using the Tesseract OCR engine, which is capable of recognizing both printed and handwritten text with high accuracy. To ensure reliable extraction of address and pin code information, the system performs a series of image preprocessing steps such as grayscale conversion, binarization, thresholding, and noise removal. These processes enhance the clarity and contrast of the text regions, preparing the image for more accurate OCR processing. After extracting the complete address, the system applies pattern recognition logic to isolate and validate the pin code, ensuring accurate identification regardless of its position or format within the text. One of the standout features of the system is the real-time animation-based sorting, which visually simulates the movement of a parcel toward its respective bin based on the extracted pin code. This dynamic visualization not only provides immediate confirmation of successful sorting but also enhances the overall user experience, making the process interactive, transparent, and easy to understand. The combined use of OCR for intelligent data extraction and animated feedback for visual tracking forms the foundation of the system’s smart and automated postal sorting capabilities.

The proposed AI-based postal sorting system offers a robust, scalable, and user-friendly solution to overcome the limitations of traditional manual sorting. By combining OCR-driven address extraction, intelligent pin code-based classification, animated visualization, and structured data storage, the system significantly improves the speed, accuracy, and traceability of postal operations. Its design ensures clear role-based access, smooth user workflows, and efficient handling of both successful and failed sorting attempts. Looking ahead, the system can be further enhanced with physical automation components such as robotic arms and conveyor belt mechanisms, enabling seamless integration of software and hardware for fully autonomous sorting operations. The addition of barcode scanning, advanced deep learning-based recognition models, and real-time item tracking can further optimize performance and expand the system’s applicability in larger-scale logistics centers and high-volume sorting environments.

\section{MODULE DESCRIPTION}

\subsection{OCR and Address Extraction Module}
The OCR and Address Extraction Module is the core AI processing unit of the postal sorting system. It processes each uploaded or captured image of letters and parcels using Tesseract OCR to accurately extract printed address details from the item. This includes reading the recipient's name, locality, city, and most importantly, the 6-digit PIN code required for sorting. Once the text is extracted, the module cleans and parses it using regular expressions to identify the relevant address components in a structured manner. Implemented using pytesseract within the Flask backend, this module ensures high accuracy in address recognition and efficient data extraction without relying on advanced NLP models, enabling seamless automated sorting workflows.

\subsection{Sorting and Mapping Module}
The Sorting and Mapping Module is responsible for the classification and decision-making process within the system. After receiving the extracted PIN code from the OCR module, it maps this PIN code to a predefined virtual bin or dispatch zone based on a configured sorting logic table. Each PIN corresponds to a specific delivery region or zone, and the system uses this mapping to determine the correct bin assignment for the item. This emulates how real postal sorting machines classify items into physical bins or conveyors for dispatch preparation. The module is implemented using Python dictionaries for static mappings or dynamic database lookups, ensuring fast, reliable, and flexible sorting operations adaptable to changes in regional postal assignments.

\subsection{Tracking \& Admin Dashboard Module}
The Tracking \& Admin Dashboard Module serves as a vital component for comprehensive tracking, monitoring, and administrative control over all postal items processed within the system. This module logs detailed records of each sorted item, including date and time of processing, extracted address text, PIN code, assigned bin or dispatch zone, and the processing user, storing this data securely in a Mysql database for future reference. It features a user-friendly admin dashboard that displays these records in a structured, searchable, and filterable table, enabling administrators to track each postal item's sorting history, verify operational accuracy, and ensure accountability across all workflows. Additionally, the module provides functionalities for filtering records by date or PIN code, generating operational reports, and monitoring daily performance, which are essential for audits and management decisions. This module is implemented using Flask for backend management, HTML templates and Bootstrap for the dashboard interface, and MYsql for database operations, ensuring robustness and efficiency in managing postal sorting activities.

\section{FEASIBILITY STUDY}
The feasibility study assesses the practicality of implementing the postal sorting automation system using OCR (Optical Character Recognition) and image processing. It considers operational, technical, and economic factors to determine whether the system can be successfully developed, deployed, and used in real-world postal services.

\subsection{Operational Feasibility}
The proposed system simplifies the existing manual postal sorting process by offering a simulated web-based platform that utilizes OCR for automated image-based sorting. This removes dependency on physical sorting infrastructure and human classification efforts. Users (postal staff) can upload or capture parcel images, which the system automatically processes to extract address and PIN code data.

The user interface is intuitive and easy to navigate, making it accessible even for non-technical staff. Role-based authentication (Admin and Staff) ensures that control and operational duties are well-managed and securely distributed. Given the reduced manual workload, improved accuracy, and increased transparency, the system is likely to be readily accepted by end-users. Furthermore, since it replicates sorting logic visually, it is suitable for both practical use and educational training.

\subsection{Technical Feasibility}
The project is technically feasible and relies entirely on open-source, lightweight technologies. The backend is powered by Python Flask, a framework known for its speed and scalability, while the frontend is built with HTML, CSS, Bootstrap, and JavaScript to ensure a responsive interface. For OCR, the system uses the Tesseract engine along with OpenCV for image preprocessing—both well-established tools in the field of computer vision.

The database layer is handled by MySQL, a reliable and widely adopted relational database system. These technologies are compatible with standard computer hardware, requiring no specialized setup. The architecture supports fast development cycles, smooth deployment, and easy scalability. Given the maturity and community support of the chosen tools, there are no significant technical barriers to project implementation.

\subsection{Economic Feasibility}
The economic feasibility of the system is highly favorable. All software components (Tesseract, Flask, MySQL, OpenCV, etc.) are open-source and do not involve any licensing costs. The system does not require costly hardware or industrial postal sorters; instead, it emulates the sorting process through software-based animations. This makes it particularly well-suited for regional post offices or training institutions with limited budgets.

By automating the sorting process, the system reduces labor dependency and long-term operational costs. It is a sustainable and affordable alternative to conveyor-based solutions, offering a realistic simulation environment that can enhance decision-making, training, and academic learning. This ensures not only a cost-effective deployment but also long-term economic viability.

